      { q: 'Explain how behavioural economics challenges the assumption of rational economic agents.', marks: 4, tier: 'amber', modelAnswer: 'Traditional economics assumes agents maximise utility/profit with perfect information (1 mark). Behavioural economics identifies systematic biases such as anchoring, loss aversion, or present bias (1 mark). These lead to predictable departures from rational choice (1 mark). For example, loss aversion means people weigh losses more heavily than equivalent gains, leading to sub-optimal decisions (1 mark).' }
